div.div:
Remember:
When aiming for a place or a goal, it is much easier to get lost, or miss the goal, than arrive. There are many more places in the world that are not your destination, while there is only one destination. In fact, one could posit an infinite amount of possible places, whereas there is only one place that is your destination.
As a consquence, the point you choose becomes the most difficult point to find or attain - unless you are already there, or you have been there before.

Remember that next time you complain about your situation...
There is that one point (place) you imagined you want to be. You spent time and effort on visualing this point. You colour it, build it, make it. You see the line (generally a straght line) to that point.
But when you arrive at that place - it is not quite as you imagined/visualised it to be. And you are dissapointed.
1. More likely to find other point
(i) If p is a pt. ~p is all that is NOT p.
(ii) That specific point that is equal and opposite to p.
This is the philosophic road of separation.
